better_2: I believe that the study should be more broad or more broad in some areas. There’s many patients with SB who have issues with neurogenic bladder/bowel, and we cannot feel those areas. So that means it could be a huge factor in leaks/accidents. It is something that should be addressed/added. Also you should ask more questions about the specific type of SB an individual has, and any major medical history ( surgery, etc). I liked the simplicity of most of it. I also think y’all should address the adaptive measures we might take, that helps relieve anxiety/stress. For those without resources, it would be cool if you offered resources, or gift cards to urology equipment (like a medical equipment site). I also addressed my concern for the time limit. We are disabled. We already have complications and family, and medical needs that have to be addressed. Personally I have a 2yr old, 3yr old and my husband works 6am, to 6pm most nights. I can’t bathe the children or myself, on my own. He has to help me, and after that we put them to bed. Sometimes we fall asleep with children. Another addition would be asking patients if they would like a reminder text. I think it would be good to extend to time limit from 5-7 hours to 12-18 hours. Also a spell check would be good, as this question says ‘use’ instead of us. Another point would be having a longer term study. I have a few good weeks in between my bad weeks. So I’m more prone to accidents when my back and nerve pain flare up. General numbness, neuropathic numbness and pain levels could also be evaluated, as that can have effects on incontinence. I know I feel more inclined to an accident when my legs feel like jello.
An option to describe / explain on each question

I liked this study and would love to do more because I think there needs to be more things done about it and spina bifida and the difficulties of living with spina bifida and disabilities that deal with bladder and bowel issues

better_2: I think for incontinence, asking a specific menstrual question/section would be very beneficial. That’s when i take pain meds that make my bladder worse (Midol contains a diuretic). That’s when i have more frequency and pressure on my bladder bc of bloating, so I'm more nervous/stressed/anxious about leaks than other times of the month, even if i didn't leak that day. And the ""health"" question didn't seem to encompass it properly since i was healthy, just on my period. Another thing that would be good to include was feelings of urgency where i made it to the bathroom in time, and didn't leak, but it still caused me lots of stress, and i would've leaked if i was further away from the bathroom. The urgency stuff really mentally affects me getting anxious etc and affects when i choose to do activities or not do activities. I liked how you asked about anxious and stressed because those are 2 different things, and that worked well.
